http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/Youth-summit-gets-under-way/article14024457.ece

Kerala is proud of its youth who are very active in social fields, Chief Minister Oommen Chandy has said.He was speaking after declaring open Yuva Varsham 2016, a three-day international youth summit organised by the Kerala State Youth Welfare Board, in association with the Rajiv Gandhi National Institute of Youth Development, Chennai, in Thiruvananthapuram on Wednesday.The Chief Minister said a student entrepreneurship policy was first announced in the State in September 2012, during the Emerging Kerala meet. Under the policy, a lot of incentives were available to students who came forward with new ideas to start their own enterprises. The response was very positive, and the policy was being continued. Two weeks ago, Prime Minister Narendra Modi had announced the Start-up India policy for the nation. However, the State had launched its own start-up policy three years before, Mr. Chandy said.Minister for Youth Affairs P.K. Jayalakshmi delivered the presidential address.P.S. Prasanth, vice chairman of the board, welcomed the gathering. The meet is aimed at discussing the problems in the fields of health, education, and employment, and giving training to solve these with the support of various organisations and government machinery.Youth from various States and outside the country are taking part in the meet.Symposiums on ‘Youth development – theory, policy, and challenges,’ ‘Interventions for youth development – innovative approaches and strategies,’ and ‘Youth development – international perspectives and experiences’ and seminar too will be held.